      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Set up the coating station",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Set up three bowls. Put the {{plain-flour}} of plain flour in the first; season with salt and pepper. Beat the {{buttermilk}} with the {{eggs}} egg in the second. In the third, mix the {{polenta}} of fine polenta with the {{paprika-smoked}} of smoked paprika, a pinch of {{cayenne}}, {{sea-salt-fine}} of salt, and {{black-pepper}} of black pepper.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Coat the tomatoes",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Working one slice at a time, dip each {{tomato}} tomato slice first in the flour, shaking off the excess; then in the buttermilk and egg mixture; then press both sides firmly into the seasoned polenta. Place on a board while you coat the remaining slices.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Fry",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Heat the {{vegetable-oil}} in a large frying pan over medium-high heat to about 175°C.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Fry the tomato slices in batches of 3 or 4 for 2 to 3 minutes per side until the crust is deep golden and the tomato has softened slightly.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Drain on kitchen paper. Serve immediately with hot sauce, soured cream, or a remoulade.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Press the polenta coating firmly onto the tomato after the buttermilk dip. The oil should sizzle straight away when a slice goes in.",
              "cause": "Coating not adhered properly, or oil not hot enough",
              "symptom": "Coating is falling off in the oil"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Use fully unripe, completely green tomatoes; slice 1 cm thick, thinner slices collapse before the crust sets",
              "cause": "Tomatoes not green enough, or sliced too thinly",
              "symptom": "Tomato slices have gone mushy"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Fry in batches; allow the oil to return to temperature between batches",
              "cause": "Oil not hot enough, or too many slices added at once",
              "symptom": "Crust is pale and soft"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Fried green tomatoes are a practical Southern American dish: at the end of the growing season, before the first frost, tomato plants still have unripe fruit with no time to ripen. Frying them was a way to use produce that would otherwise go to waste. The dish became widely known outside the South through the 1991 film of the same name, though it had been a regional staple for well over a century by then. The polenta crust is the Southern version; a breadcrumb version also exists in the Midwest.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
